<DOC><DOCNO> AP881024-0253 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-24-88 1727EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     10-24 0549</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0570</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Rallies; Gold Prices Fall</HEAD><HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD><BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE><BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar rose Monday, partly in reaction to aTreasury Department report that said strength in the dollar thisyear would not slow down reduction of the huge U.S. trade deficit.   Gold prices fell $3 an ounce or more following an inconclusiveweekend meeting of eight oil producers. Republic National Bank ofNew York said gold bullion was bid at $405.50 a troy ounce as of 4p.m. EDT, down from $408.50 an ounce late Friday.   In a report required by Congress, the Treasury Department saidit did not expect the dollar's rise from its lows of January to``significantly alter'' prospects for continued progress onshrinking the trade gap.   Some currency traders saw the report as a sign that the Reaganadministration was not in favor of a continued fall in the dollar.   ``It's the first salvo just to give notice to the market that itis not a one-way street,'' said Charles E. Minnaar, a vicepresident at Chase Manhattan Bank.   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business daybegins, the dollar edged up 0.20 yen to a closing 126.60. Later, inLondon, it was quoted at the same rate. In New York, the dollarrose to 127.02 yen from 126.28 yen late Friday.   In London, the dollar rose against the British pound, which wasquoted at $1.7520, cheaper than $1.7620 late Friday. In New York,the pound fell to $1.7501 from $1.7615 Friday.   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Friday'srates, included: 1.7898 West German marks, up from 1.7778; 1.5175Swiss francs, up from 1.5061; 1.1986 Canadian dollars, down from1.1992; 6.1100 French francs, up from 6.0900; and 1,332.88 Italianlire, up from 1,327.50.   The New York rates are based on quotes before the TreasuryDepartment report was issued to Congress at 4 p.m. EDT. An hourafter that, the dollar was at 1.7930 West German marks, 126.97 yenand 1.7485 British pounds.   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Friday'srates, included: 1.7860 West German marks, down from 1.7875; 1.5145Swiss francs, up from 1.5135; 6.1025 French francs, down from6.1115; 2.0143 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0170; 1,330.85 Italianlire, down from 1,332.50; and 1.1973 Canadian dollars, down from1.2022.   Bullion dealers said the slide in gold prices followed thefailure of eight member nations of the Organization of PetroleumExporting Countries to reach any firm agreement on restrainingproduction during a meeting in Spain.   They said a tip toward the bearish side on the technical chartsadded to the downward pressure on gold.   In Hong Kong, gold closed at $408.20 a troy ounce bid, down from$411.10 an ounce on Saturday. In London, gold fell to $405.15 anounce from $410.15 late Friday. In Zurich, it fell to $405.50 anounce from $409.40 late Friday.   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for currentdelivery fell to $405.80 a troy ounce from $408.40 an ounce Friday.   Silver was quoted in London on Monday at a late bid of $6.23 atroy ounce, down from Friday's $6.28. On New York's Comex, silverbullion for current delivery fell to $6.197 a troy ounce from$6.223 Friday.</TEXT></DOC>